So, you're finally ready to give your walls a fresh coat of paint. Maybe you've been staring at that faded beige in the living room for way too long, or maybe you're moving into a new space and want to make it yours. Either way, it’s time to call in the pros. But how do you actually find the right painter for the job?

Spoiler alert: it’s not just about the cheapest quote or the flashiest website. Choosing the right painter is a mix of asking smart questions, trusting your gut, and doing just a tiny bit of homework. Don’t worry — we’ve got your back.
Here’s a cheat sheet of the most important questions to ask before you hire a painter (plus a few tips to avoid any “I wish I’d known…” regrets).

1. Are You Licensed and Insured?
Let’s start with the basics. A professional painter should have the proper license (if your state requires it) and insurance. Why does this matter? Because if something goes wrong — like a ladder through your window or paint spilled on your new hardwood floors — you want to be covered. No insurance = potential disaster.
Pro Tip: Ask for proof of insurance and make sure it includes both liability and workers' comp.

2. How Much Experience Do You Have?
Everyone has to start somewhere, but do you really want your first-ever paint job to be someone’s test run? Look for painters who have experience with projects similar to yours — whether it’s exterior, interior, commercial, or specialty finishes.
Bonus question: Ask if they have before-and-after photos of previous jobs. A good painter is proud of their work.

3. Can You Share References or Reviews?
Any reputable painter should have happy clients willing to vouch for them. Whether it’s word-of-mouth, Yelp, or Google reviews, pay attention to what people are saying. Are they consistent, on-time, neat? Or are there complaints about poor communication and sloppy work?
Don’t be shy: Call a reference or two. A five-minute chat can save you a lot of headaches later.

4. What’s Included in Your Quote?
Not all quotes are created equal. Some painters throw out a number and hope for the best, while others break it down so you know exactly what you’re paying for.
Ask about:
Prep work (patching holes, sanding, priming)
Paint quality and brand
Number of coats
Cleanup
Timeline
Red flag: If it’s vague or seems too good to be true, it probably is.

5. Do You Provide a Written Contract?
Verbal agreements are fine — until they’re not. Always get a written contract outlining the scope of work, timeline, payment schedule, and warranty (if any). This protects both you and the painter.
And yes, even if it’s a family friend or your cousin’s cousin, get it in writing.

6. What Kind of Paint Do You Use?
Not all paint is created equal. Some brands cover better, last longer, or have lower VOCs (read: fewer fumes). Ask what brand they recommend and why. If you have allergies, pets, or kids, this matters even more.
Also: Who buys the paint? Some painters include it in their price, while others expect you to purchase it separately.

7. How Will You Protect My Furniture and Floors?
This might seem obvious, but you’d be surprised how many people forget to ask. A good painter will take the time to cover your furniture, tape off edges, and protect your floors like their own.
Ask: Will you move furniture? What kind of drop cloths do you use?

8. What Happens If Something Goes Wrong?
What if the color doesn’t turn out the way you thought? Or the finish isn’t right? Good painters will work with you to make it right — but only if you’ve talked about it ahead of time.
Ask about: Satisfaction guarantees, touch-ups, and how changes or issues are handled during the project.

Final Thoughts
Hiring the right painter doesn’t have to be stressful. Ask the right questions, trust your instincts, and don’t rush into the lowest bid. You’re not just paying for someone to slap paint on a wall — you’re hiring someone to improve your space, your vibe, and maybe even your mood every time you walk in the room.
So take your time, do your homework, and remember: a great paint job is worth it.
